        </div>
      </header>

      <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none space-y-6 text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground [&_h2]:text-foreground [&_h2]:text-2xl [&_h2]:font-bold [&_h2]:mt-10 [&_h2]:mb-4 [&_h3]:text-foreground [&_h3]:text-xl [&_h3]:font-semibold [&_h3]:mt-8 [&_h3]:mb-3 [&_strong]:text-foreground [&_a]:text-primary [&_a]:underline [&_a:hover]:text-foreground">

        <h2>The Short Version</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Most nicotine pouch side effects are mild, temporary, and entirely avoidable</strong>.
          Tingling lips, hiccups, a wave of nausea — these are almost always caused by one thing:
          using a pouch that is too strong for your current tolerance. The fix is straightforward.
          Drop down in strength, give your body time to adjust, and the discomfort disappears. According to Public Health England and clinical guidance, these reactions are normal physiological responses to nicotine exposure and pose no lasting harm.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you are new to <a href="/blog/what-are-nicotine-pouches">nicotine pouches</a>, none
          of this should put you off. Millions of adults use them daily without issues. But knowing
          what to expect — and why it happens — means you can skip the unpleasant learning curve
          that catches some first-timers off guard. If you are still choosing your first product,
          our <a href="/blog/best-nicotine-pouches-for-beginners-2026">beginner's guide</a> walks you
          through exactly where to start.
        </p>

        <h2>Common Side Effects</h2>
        <p>
          Here is what you might experience, what causes it, and what to do about it.
        </p>

        <h3>Tingling or Burning Under the Lip</h3>
        <p>
          This is the most common sensation and it is <strong>completely normal</strong>. Nicotine
          pouches contain a pH adjuster (usually sodium carbonate) that makes the lining of your
          gum more permeable so the nicotine can absorb efficiently. That mild tingle or slight
          burn is the pH shift doing its job. It typically <strong>fades within two to five minutes</strong>
          as the pouch settles in.
        </p>
        <p>
          Mini pouches and lower strengths produce less tingling because they contain less pH
          adjuster. If the sensation bothers you, try a <a href="/products/strength/mild">mild
          strength (2-4 mg)</a> pouch or switch to a mini format. The tingle is not a sign of
          damage — it is simply how the product works.
        </p>

        <h3>Hiccups</h3>
        <p>
          Hiccups are <strong>very common</strong>, especially with stronger pouches above 8 mg.
          Nicotine stimulates the vagus nerve, which runs from the brain to the abdomen, and this
          can trigger involuntary diaphragm contractions — hiccups. They are harmless but annoying,
          and they are a reliable signal that the strength is too high for you right now.
        </p>
        <p>
          The solution is simple: step down by 2-4 mg. If you are getting hiccups on a 10 mg pouch,
          try a 6 mg instead. For help picking the right level, read our guide on
          <a href="/blog/how-to-choose-your-strength">how to choose your strength</a>.
        </p>

        <h3>Nausea or Dizziness</h3>
        <p>
          Feeling queasy or lightheaded after placing a pouch is a clear sign that <strong>the
          nicotine dose exceeds your tolerance</strong>. This happens most often to beginners who
          start with a strong pouch, or to experienced users who jump up in strength too quickly.
        </p>
        <p>
          If it happens, <strong>remove the pouch immediately</strong>. Drink water. Sit down if you
          feel dizzy. The sensation passes within 10-15 minutes. Next time, try a pouch that is
          2-4 mg lower. Using pouches on an empty stomach makes nausea much more likely, so eat
          something first — especially during your first week. Our
          <a href="/blog/best-nicotine-pouches-for-beginners-2026">beginner's guide</a> covers this in detail.
        </p>

        <h3>Dry Mouth</h3>
        <p>
          Nicotine mildly reduces saliva production, and some users notice a <strong>slight dryness</strong>
          in the mouth during or after use. This is not harmful and does not indicate anything wrong.
          Keep a glass of water nearby and sip regularly. Staying hydrated generally solves it. If you
          are browsing for your next order, check out our <a href="/nicotine-pouches">full catalogue</a>
          — some moist-format pouches feel less drying than others.
        </p>

        <h3>Gum Irritation</h3>
        <p>
          Placing multiple pouches per day in the <strong>same spot</strong> can irritate the gum
          tissue. You might notice redness, tenderness, or a slight soreness where the pouch sits.
          The fix is to <strong>rotate placement</strong> — alternate between the left and right
          sides of your upper lip, and vary the exact position slightly each time.
        </p>
        <p>
          Take breaks between pouches. If irritation persists after a day or two of reduced use,
          give your gums a full rest for 48 hours. Heavy daily use in one spot is the cause —
          the pouches themselves are soft and designed to be gentle on tissue.
        </p>

        <h2>Strength Is Almost Always the Problem</h2>
        <p>
          Notice a pattern? Nearly every side effect traces back to nicotine strength. Here is a
          quick-reference table:
        </p>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <th class="text-left py-3 pr-4 text-foreground font-semibold">Side Effect</th>
                <th class="text-left py-3 pr-4 text-foreground font-semibold">Likely Cause</th>
                <th class="text-left py-3 text-foreground font-semibold">Fix</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
