              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border/50">
                <td class="py-3 pr-4">Dry mouth</td>
                <td class="py-3 pr-4">Nicotine reduces saliva</td>
                <td class="py-3">Drink water alongside</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-3 pr-4">Gum irritation</td>
                <td class="py-3 pr-4">Repeated use in same spot</td>
                <td class="py-3">Rotate placement, take breaks</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2>How to Avoid Side Effects</h2>
        <p>
          Prevention is easier than management. Follow these five rules and you will sidestep
          the vast majority of problems:
        </p>
        <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-3">
          <li><strong>Start with the lowest strength available.</strong> A 2-4 mg pouch is plenty for anyone without existing nicotine tolerance. You can always move up — you cannot undo a bad first experience. Browse our <a href="/products/strength/mild">mild range</a> to see options.</li>
          <li><strong>Do not use on an empty stomach.</strong> Nicotine hits harder without food in your system. Eat a meal or snack before your first pouch of the day, especially in your first week.</li>
          <li><strong>Avoid combining with coffee at first.</strong> Both nicotine and caffeine are stimulants. Together they can amplify nausea and dizziness. Once you know your tolerance, combining them is fine — but not on day one.</li>
          <li><strong>Use one pouch at a time.</strong> Doubling up does not improve the experience. It doubles the nicotine dose and doubles the chance of side effects.</li>
          <li><strong>Give your body time to adjust.</strong> The first three to five pouches might feel unusual. A slight tingle, an odd sensation under the lip — this is normal. It fades as you get accustomed to the format.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          If you are <a href="/blog/switching-from-cigarettes-to-nicotine-pouches">switching from
          cigarettes</a>, your nicotine tolerance is already established — but the delivery method
          is different. Start at a moderate strength (6-8 mg) rather than jumping straight to
          extra strong.
        </p>

        <h2>When to Stop or See a Doctor</h2>
        <p>
          In the vast majority of cases, lowering your strength or taking a break resolves any
          discomfort within minutes. However, <strong>stop using nicotine pouches and seek medical
          advice</strong> if you experience any of the following:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>Chest pain or tightness</li>
          <li>Irregular or rapid heartbeat</li>
          <li>Severe or persistent nausea that does not resolve after removing the pouch</li>
          <li>Allergic reactions such as swelling, rash, or difficulty breathing</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Nicotine is an addictive substance. If you do not currently use nicotine, be aware that
          regular use of nicotine pouches can create dependence. <strong>We are a shop, not a
          clinic</strong> — this guide is based on common user experiences, not medical advice. If
          you have concerns about nicotine use and your health, speak to a healthcare professional.
        </p>

        <h2>Nicotine-Free Options</h2>
        <p>
          If you want the ritual — the pouch under the lip, the flavour, the moment of calm —
          without any nicotine at all, there are <strong>0 mg options</strong> available. Brands
          like <a href="/brands/zeronito">Zeronito</a> and X-booster make tobacco-free,
          nicotine-free pouches in a range of flavours. Zero nicotine means zero nicotine-related
          side effects. They are a solid choice if you are curious about the format but not ready
          to introduce nicotine, or if you are looking to step down from nicotine gradually.
        </p>

      </div>

